<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Inchcape sells motor rental businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Inchcape, the international motors, services and marketing group, has sold
its remaining car and van rental businesses to a management buy-out for
Pounds 29.75m.
The sale of Kenning Car and Van Rental (KCVR) and United Rental Group had
been expected, and represents the final phase of streamlining following the
acquisitions of TKM and Hogg Group.
The buy-out was backed by venture capital group 3i, which has put together a
Pounds 100m financing package to cover the purchase price and an additional
off balance sheet debt of Pounds 70m related to the vehicle fleets.
Mr Chris Rowlands, director of 3i's Birmingham office, said the two
companies had made a total operating profit of about Pounds 4.5m last year.
3i has put together Pounds 17m of equity funding, while Barclays arranged
Pounds 15.5m of debt. The management will own about 40 per cent of the
company's shares.
KCVR was purchased by Inchcape as part of the Pounds 383m acquisition of TKM
in March 1992, while United was part of Hogg Group, which was bought in
June. Their combined fleets, including vehicles operated by franchisees,
amount to 25,000 vehicles and the two companies operate through more than
200 outlets.
Mr Kevin Betts, former finance director at Central TV, is to be chairman,
and David Hardman will be chief executive. 3i said there had been
competition for the deal from other vehicle rental companies and also
venture capital groups.
