<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / UK Company News: The rising cost of running Kwik Save
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Graeme Bowler, chief executive of grocery discounter Kwik Save since July
1993, was paid a total of Pounds 586,000 in his first year - 72 per cent
more than his predecessor Mr Graeme Seabrook received in his final nine
months with the company.
Kwik Save's annual report, published yesterday, showed that it had to pay Mr
Bowler a substantial premium to lure him away from his position as managing
director of Franklins discount stores in Australia. On an annualised basis,
Mr Bowler received about 30 per cent more than his predecessor.
'We paid a lot to get the right man,' the company said. 'Discounting is a
very competitive business, and this is a man we went half-way round the
world to get.'
Kwik Save added that Mr Bowler, 55, had to be persuaded to leave an
attractive position in Australia, and spend what may be the rest of his
working life in the UK.
The report shows that Mr Bowler earned a basic Pounds 260,000 in the year to
August 27, some 45 per cent higher than Mr Seabrook's Pounds 179,000 in his
final nine months.
His benefits in kind were 53 per cent greater, at Pounds 40,000, while his
bonus was more than twice as much, at Pounds 245,000 compared with Mr
Seabrook's Pounds 105,000.
His pension contributions were Pounds 41,000, against Mr Seabrook's Pounds
31,000.
</TEXT>
