<TEXT>
Pillar Property Investments, the investment and development company which
joined the stock market in August, announced pre-tax profits of Pounds
34,000, the purchase of a shopping centre and a new director, writes Simon
London.
The result for the six months to September 30 was struck after charging
Pounds 2.17m interest on loan stock which was repaid on flotation. Mr
Raymond Mould, chairman, said Pillar had moved strongly into profit since
then.
The company did not publish comparative half-year figures but in the nine
months to the end of March pre-tax profits were Pounds 744,000.
Pillar also announced the acquisition of the Fairhill Shopping Centre in
Ballymena, Northern Ireland for Pounds 11.5m, through its joint venture with
SITQ Immobilier, the Canadian investment fund. The joint venture has now
spent Pounds 62m on shopping centres out of a potential budget of Pounds
250m.
Mr Mould added that Pillar was in advanced negotiations for the acquisition
of a number of other investment properties.
Mr Nicholas Sheehan will join the board in January following the departure
of Mr Robert Maxted, property director, in October. Until March, Mr Sheehan
was chief executive of London &amp; Edinburgh Trust, the development company.
