<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / Observer: Seconds out
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
When 46-year-old boxer George Foreman last month regained the world
heavyweight championship, big bucks were sure to follow. Now he's being
offered an estimated Dollars 2m per advertising endorsement, or two thirds
of the total income he earned for ads last year.
Advertisers are hoping Foreman - a preacher as well as prize-fighter - will
remain a suitable member of the shrivelled ranks of squeaky-clean sporting
figures useful for such endorsements; possession of no unsightly stains is
now a sine qua non in the US endorsement market, whose fingers have been
badly burned by the likes of Michael Jackson.
So you can now buy a Foreman-autographed glove in a display case for Dollars
399.95, or a rather cheaper signed photo of Foreman seconds after his
November 5 victory over Michael Moorer.
How long before he is endorsing slimming products?
</TEXT>
