FT  06 DEC 94 / Directors worried about losing staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WOLFFE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More directors are concerned about losing staff than about the skills
shortage, according to a survey of job trends published today.
In a poll of more than 400 companies across the UK, one in four senior
directors said retaining employees was the most important issue in human
resources.
A similar poll in April revealed that more directors were concerned about
the lack of skills among employees. The skills gap now ranks second in the
list of personnel priorities, with 20 per cent of directors citing it as
their most pressing problem.
Mr Alec Reed, chairman of Reed Personnel Services, which carried out the
telephone poll at the end of last month, said: 'While companies are
confident that salary rises will be held at an average of 3.2 per cent, they
are already feeling the effects of a tighter labour market, with its
attendant pressures.'
