<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / Phone groups face December revolution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Oftel, the UK telecommunications regulator, issues a consultative paper this
week which will lead to the most far-reaching changes in industry
regulations since the privatisation of British Telecommunications in 1984.
Some of the changes could have profound implications for the cost of
telephone services - currently on a downward trend - in both the residential
and business sectors.
The 'December Document' is ostensibly about the cost to the growing number
of public telecommunications operators of interconnection to the BT network.
Any public telephone operator in the UK has to link to BT's network at some
point to deliver a service, and interconnection charges can represent
between a half and two-thirds of an operator's costs. Oftel has been
fielding a torrent of complaints that the regime is unfair, arbitrary and
inimical to business planning.
The document will tackle this problem and account separation - through which
BT can be measured on the performance of each of its operations - in detail.
But Mr Don Cruickshank, director-general of Oftel, is also taking the
opportunity to explore a range of questions - many with no easy answer -
which have been thrown up by the complex development of the
telecommunications industry.
These range from the 'universal service obligation' - the need to provide a
service on economic terms to the isolated, disabled and infirm - to the
measures which should be taken to regulate the industry's most recent
entrants, the suppliers of multimedia services which are not themselves
telecommunications operators.
There are also suggestions that Mr Cruickshank will seek to open a debate
over the future of Oftel itself, asking at what point the role of the
regulator should cease to exist in a freely competitive market.
Some of the more important questions to be addressed this week are:
How to set interconnection charges to allow operators flexibility in pricing
their own services. At present, interconnection charges paid are directly
related to BT's tariff structure because BT connects its competitors' calls
at commercial rates. In other words, because interconnection is such an
important element of an operator's costs, its freedom for price innovation
is constrained by BT's pricing strategy. One answer is to relate pricing to
capacity; a fear is that many newer entrants have insufficient information
to calculate their capacity requirements.
How to resolve the nightmarish issue of the 'access deficit contribution'
(ADC). BT, as owner of the nationwide network, is obliged to provide a
universal service at reasonable cost. It is prevented by Oftel from raising
line rental charges by more than the retail prices index plus 2 per cent
annually. This protects vulnerable residential users but the subsequent lack
of 'rebalancing' costs BT revenue.
The argument is that all operators should make a contribution to these costs
 -an ADC. Sir Bryan Carsberg, the previous director-general, ruled that to
help entrants, operators pay no ADC until they reached a specific market
share. At the moment only Mercury pays ADCs.
The complexities of calculating the charges are daunting. A principal theme
of the paper is expected to be the way the telecommunications market is
becoming buried under a tangle of regulations, and the need to simplify
matters for all competitors.
How to define and calculate the universal service obligation. For such a
central issue it is remarkable that no formal definition exists, nor an
estimate of how much it costs to provide.
Oftel will attempt a definition and look at ways of identifying costs. It is
likely to make clear that it will be a cost for the operators to bear rather
than a tax on the public.
Responses to the paper are invited before the end of March and the new
framework is expected to be published in the summer.
The debate will be followed with intense interest not only in the UK but by
telecommunications authorities and companies in Europe and beyond. It is
asking the questions they all have to answer.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Telecommunications.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9631 Regulation, Administration of Utilities.
    P4813 Telephone Communications, Ex Radio.
</IN>
