<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / Tube plans restart of tunnelling: Austrian method guidelines
listed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London Underground has submitted plans for restarting work on part of the
Pounds 1.9bn Jubilee line extension using the controversial New Austrian
Tunnelling Method.
Work was halted as a precaution on two Jubilee line stations after a tunnel
being excavated using the method collapsed under Heathrow airport in
October.
Plans for restarting work on the Jubilee line stations have been submitted
to the Health and Safety Executive which is conducting an investigation into
the Heathrow collapse and the suitability of using the method in London
clay.
The executive has asked contractors working on the Jubilee line extension
and the Pounds 300m rail link from Heathrow to Paddington station in central
London not to use the method until they are satisfied that proposed designs
and construction procedures are safe.
Mr Hugh Doherty, project director for the Jubilee line extension, said
yesterday: 'We would hope to resume work as soon as possible but cannot say
whether this will be before or after Christmas. The stoppage only affects
two out of 11 stations on the extension. The bulk of work is continuing
normally.'
The Health and Safety Executive yesterday published a discussion paper which
included a proposed checklist of procedures which it recommends should be
adopted by designers and contractors opting to use the method.
The Austrian technique, which has been used internationally for about 40
years, encourages engineers to utilise the strength of the ground
surrounding a tunnel to minimise the extra strengthening required to prevent
collapse during construction.
The technique can be up to 25 per cent cheaper than conventional tunnelling
methods.
The executive said the success of the method depended upon precise
predictions of ground responses to excavation together with sophisticated
measuring procedures to allow engineers time to strengthen the tunnel if
there were unexpected movements.
Investigators into the Heathrow collapse are concentrating their inquiries
on the possibility that it may have been caused by human error or design
problems.
The use of NATM in the UK. HSE, Heathrow Investigation Project, Rose Court,
2 Southwark Bridge. London SE1 9HS.
</TEXT>
