<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / City levy 'may fund transport infrastructure'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Transport projects in London and other large cities could be financed by a
business levy similar to the non-domestic rate, under proposals put forward
by the Corporation of London yesterday.
Businesses would be able to vote on whether to support the levy in their
area - though they would have to abide by the majority decision - and would
be involved in monitoring how it was being spent.
A study by Mr Tony Travers and Mr Stephen Glaister of the London School of
Economics, on behalf of the corporation, includes plans for an
infrastructure fund for London to complement the government's
private-finance initiative.
The Treasury yesterday reacted negatively to the proposal, saying it would
increase the burden on business at a time when rates were due to fall and
that it did not represent 'true private finance'.
The City first began looking at methods of raising additional finance for
transport when CrossRail, a plan for a cross-London rail line, was mooted.
Another 1p in the pound on business rates in Greater London could raise
Pounds 75m a year towards the capital cost of transport schemes or to the
repayment of interest on loans. The scheme's managers could expect to raise
10 times their annual revenue from the levy in the form of commercial loans.
Mr Travers said: 'London's infrastructure is badly in need of reinvestment
but government funding has remained below the levels officially accepted as
necessary to reinstate and maintain the railway network.'
The infrastructure fund would be easy to understand because the rating
system already exists and it would be relatively easy and cheap to collect
the levy, Mr Glaister said.
The idea is for a trust or similar organisation to be established, combining
private and public-sector membership. It would devise a package of transport
schemes seeking backing and propose this to local businesses.
The government would have to commit itself to maintaining existing
public-spending levels for transport if businesses were to be expected to
contribute, Mr Travers said.
Legislation would be needed to permit the introduction of a levy. Some US
cities have designated improvement districts, which raise funds from local
business. In France, a city may impose a levy on businesses to finance
transport infrastructure.
An Infrastructure Fund for London. Corporation of London. 071-332 3451.
</TEXT>
