<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / Lloyd's faces resistance to deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Efforts by Lloyd's of London to reach a deal to end legal action by
lossmaking members are facing resistance from those who would have to pay
most of the bill, the insurance market's ruling council is expected to hear
tomorrow, Ralph Atkins writes.
It emerged yesterday that Mr Peter Middleton, Lloyd's chief executive, last
Wednesday met 'errors and omissions' insurers - providers of negligence
cover to professional agencies being sued - as part of his efforts to
increase the pressure for a new settlement.
Although E&amp;O insurers are understood to be divided over whether fresh
negotiations are in their interest, the majority believe firmly that they
have no incentive to enter talks at this stage.
Tomorrow's council meeting is expected to decide whether attempts to forge a
new deal should be stepped up.
Earlier this year Names - individuals whose assets have traditionally
supported the market - rejected a deal worth Pounds 900m and have
subsequently pursued court actions for claims totalling about Pounds 3bn.
The E&amp;O insurers argue that the sums available to fund any deal have not
changed and that lossmaking Names continue to have unrealistic expectations
about how much they might eventually receive - either through court action
or a settlement. Much of the E&amp;O cover was provided within the Lloyd's
market, funded by other Names.
</TEXT>
