<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / Money laundering in property feared
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three-quarters of property professionals and their advisers have acted in
deals which raised suspicions of money laundering, according to a survey for
solicitors Herbert Smith.
A third of those questioned said their clients included companies whose
dealings were slightly doubtful.
Most suspicious transactions involved buyers transferringfunds offshore.
Buyers willing to pay over the market rate for a property or pay in cash
were also seen as suspicious.
The Criminal Justice Act 1993 and subsequent money laundering regulations
make it a criminal offence to fail to report suspicions of laundering
involving drug-trafficking or terrorist activity.
Surveyors or estate agents could face up to five years in prison if they
harbour suspicions about a transaction and do not report it to the
authorities.
</TEXT>
