FT  06 DEC 94 / BBC urges support for move into global market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC last night appealed to the ITV companies and the Independent
Television Commission to support the corporation's move into the global
marketplace.
Mr Bob Phillis, deputy director-general, said that if the BBC was unable to
supplement the licence fee either programme quality would suffer or there
would be a revival of the argument that the BBC should carry advertising.
'I do not believe this would be in the interests of British audiences, the
British programme-making industry - or perhaps even the ITV companies,
Channel 4, Channel 5 or the cable and satellite service,' Mr Phillis told a
Royal Television Society dinner.
He said he was convinced the corporation could serve the UK audience and
compete worldwide.
To ensure that commercial activities were consistent with 'the BBC's special
qualities' and brand values, staff would today receive copies of new
commercial policy guidelines.
The guidelines will set out the sort of commercial activities which the BBC
can focus on and also give guidance on sponsorship, co-productions and
promotional activity.
Mr Phillis said: 'Producers and editors throughout the BBC must have a clear
understanding of what they should and should not do when faced with
commercial opportunity.' He also called for co-operation with the rest of
the television industry on the introduction of digital terrestrial
television.
