<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / World Trade News: Chile expected to start Nafta talks next
year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The leaders of US, Canada and Mexico are expected to announce on Sunday
their intention to begin negotiations next year over Chile's accession to
the North American Free Trade Agreement.
The announcement is being planned for the last day of the Summit of the
Americas in Miami, where President Bill Clinton is hosting a meeting of 34
heads of state and government from the western hemisphere.
Officials involved in the pre-summit deliberations say the announcement
would help to provide a symbolic climax to the meeting, which most Latin
American governments believed until recently would yield little of
substance. They say further talks are necessary before an announcement is
certain.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US Trade Representative, yesterday said: 'Our goal is
to have an interesting announcement on Sunday led by the President of the
United States and involving Chile.' Officials close to the talks said the
aim was to announce plans to begin talks soon on Chile's accession to Nafta.
Nafta, which groups the US, Canada and Mexico in a free-trade zone, came
into effect at the start of this year. The Clinton administration has often
stated its intention to negotiate free trade agreements with other Latin
American countries, with Chile the first in line - either bilaterally or
through Nafta, but has never specified a schedule.
The US had been unwilling to commit itself to extending Nafta before the
ratification of the Uruguay Round world trade agreement by the US Congress
last week. Trade officials from the three countries believe that unless
agreement is concluded over Chile's accession next year, the process will
become embroiled in the 1996 US presidential election campaign.
They admit that since the disposition of the new members of the US Congress
is still uncertain, Mr Clinton's ability to push through trade legislation
cannot be taken for granted. However, officials see a chance for passage of
a fast track authority, limited to Chile. This would avoid a line-by-line
scrutiny by the US Congress of the accession agreement, which would make
passage all but impossible.
Chile is a small economy compared to the other three - it is a sixth the
size of of Mexico's, itself a 20th of the US - and most of its exports
already enter the US at zero or low tariffs. However, an agreement is seen
as giving further comfort to investors in Chile and reduce the vulnerability
of Chilean exporters to trade disputes with the US. Most importantly, it is
viewed as providing momentum for the Nafta process. 'It's like a bicycle; if
we stop pedalling, everyone will fall off,' said one official.
Officials expect Mr Clinton, Mr Ernesto Zedillo, the new Mexican president,
and the Canadian prime minister, Mr Jean Chretien, to invite Chile's
President Eduardo Frei to join them on the podium to make the announcement.
Key to growth, page 19
</TEXT>
