<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / Soares in clash over Angola aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Mario Soares, Portugal's Socialist president, has clashed with the
centre-right government of prime minister Anibal Cavaco Silva over the issue
of Angola, Portugal's former colony. Mr Fernando Nogueira, defence minister,
tendered his resignation after Mr Soares vetoed the reappointment of General
Narcisco Mendes Dias, air force commander, because of alleged military aid
to the Angolan government. Mr Cavaco Silva rejected the resignation and
officials described the president's veto as 'deeply unjust'. By blocking the
reappointment, Mr Soares is holding Gen Mendes Dias responsible for the
alleged servicing of Angolan government fighter aircraft by a Portuguese
company, damaging Portugal's standing as a neutral arbitrator in Angola's
civil war. Newspapers have published details of the military assistance, but
the government denies knowledge of the service contracts. However, Mr
Nogueira has accepted the resignation of the head of the public-sector
company involved, saying the government should have been informed. The
dispute is the most serious clash between the president and the government
since Mr Soares was elected in 1986 and comes less than a year before the
next general election.
</TEXT>
