<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / Greek inflation falls to 10.3%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greece's yearly inflation rate fell to 10.3 per cent in October, from 11.0
per cent the previous month, according to statistics service figures
published yesterday. Monthly consumer prices rose 0.3 per cent in November
because of higher prices for food, clothes and consumer durables. The
government no longer expects to reach its target of single-digit inflation
by December but last month's decline, together with delays in raising
administered prices, makes it likely inflation can be held below 11 per cent
this year, against 12.1 per cent in 1993. Greece's inflation rate is still
more than three times the EU average.
</TEXT>
