<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / French move on political funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France looks set to ban corporate contributions to political parties after
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur said last night he had overcome his
'hesitations' about such a sweeping move to clean up French politics. He
said he would put to the National Assembly a four-point plan to stop
companies bankrolling political parties, to reduce the ceiling on spending
in next year's presidential election by 30 per cent, to introduce an audit
of politicians' personal wealth, and to improve fairness and transparency in
the award of public contracts.
Mr Balladur acknowledged that he had initially hesitated about a total ban
on corporate campaign contributions, out of concern that this would put
political parties into the hands of the state, which since 1990 has financed
a portion of their activities. But he had previously suggested a three-year
experimental freeze on companies giving to political campaigns.
Mr Balladur, who has lost three ministers to corruption charges in recent
months, cannot afford to appear lax on this issue in the run-up to the
presidential election. The National Assembly is to start debating reform on
Friday, with its conservative majority now clearly, like its Socialist and
Communist opposition, in favour of separating business and politics.
</TEXT>
