<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / EU ministers agree on loan for Ukraine: Ecu85m should pave
way for balance of payments aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EU finance ministers yesterday sent a belated signal of support for the
reformist government in Ukraine with an agreement in principle to provide an
Ecu85m (Pounds 67m) loan.
The EU loan should pave the way for an international rescue plan to fill the
looming Dollars 1bn (Pounds 610m) gap in Ukraine's fourth quarter balance of
payments, which threatened to re-ignite inflation and cut short energy
imports this winter.
The compromise in Brussels yesterday means the Ecu85m loan will be disbursed
only after the International Monetary Fund completes negotiations on a
Dollars 1.5bn standby loan to support the reform programme.
It is also tied to closure of the Chernobyl nuclear plant, though Ukraine's
promise to meet its debt arrears means that Ecu400m of EU should be released
soon to help pay for the Kiev government's nuclear clean-up.
The US and Germany lobbied hard for a deal in Brussels, arguing it was vital
to bolster President Leonid Kuchma, a central planner turned economic
reformer who campaigned for signing the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty
France and the UK - which had previously held up an accord - fell into line
after their partners agreed to impose tighter conditions on future EU
macro-economic aid to third countries, with Ukraine being treated as an
exceptional case.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the UK chancellor of the exchequer, told colleagues that
the EU should not turn itself into a 'shadow IMF'. He called for clearer
rules on EU lending to distressed countries, and a study is expected to be
produced next year.
Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister who chaired yesterday's meeting,
overcame French reservations by forging a compromise on aid to Algeria.
Ministers agreed with the Commission to provide a maximum Ecu200m to be
released in two tranches to support structural reform in the north African
state.
Mr Waigel heralded the agreement as an important statement of European
support for Mr Kuchma, who had embarked on a 'courageous and ambitious'
reform programme.
The decision on Ukraine yesterday must still go through the European
parliament, and it leaves open the question of how much the EU will be ready
to contribute next year to cope with expected balance of payments
difficulties. But in the short term, it unlocks further funds from the US
and other Group of Seven industrialised nations, including Japan. The US has
already offered around Dollars 100m, with Canada offering Dollars 25m.
Ministers also agreed to provide macro-economic aid of up to Ecu130m for
Slovakia, to be released in two tranches to help with reform.
</TEXT>
<XX>
