<DATE>941206
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 94 / Major pushes for new law on executive pay awards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent, and NORMA COHEN, Investments
Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies could be forced to secure shareholder approval for executive
salary awards under proposals to be considered by a cabinet committee next
week.
Mr John Major is pushing strongly for a change in the law to make salary
packages paid by public companies subject to an affirmative vote by
shareholders at annual meetings.
The proposal would dramatically strengthen shareholders' rarely used powers
to question directors at annual meetings.
The plan emerged from an ad hoc meeting of senior ministers convened by Mr
David Hunt, the cabinet troubleshooter, after Mr Major condemned
'unjustified' pay rises in the Commons.
The prime minister believes it would allay public anger about big pay rises
such as the 75 per cent awarded last month to Mr Cedric Brown, chief
executive of British Gas.
However, Mr Hunt referred the issue to the cabinet's industrial and consumer
affairs committee, EDI, after Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, made clear his opposition.
Mr Heseltine argued that stronger shareholder powers would make it difficult
for UK companies to recruit world-class foreign executives, who often demand
lucrative salary packages as compensation for relocation.
He told Mr Hunt that the pool of talent available to companies would be
reduced, damaging the competitiveness of British industry, if directors knew
their packages would be subject to open debate and possible rejection.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor, supports Mr Major's drive for change, partly
because of reservations about the willingness of institutional investors to
support attempts to supervise salary packages under the existing law.
The proposed change would probably require primary legislation, but the
government's small programme of 12 bills in the present parliamentary
session means that it could be brought in quickly.
The practical implications of the proposed change, including the need for
legislation, are being explored by an interdepartmental working party of
Treasury and DTI officials that will report to EDI next week.
However, the working party is being led by Mr Heseltine's officials,
suggesting that the case against the proposals is likely to be put strongly
to ministers.
Institutional fund managers dismissed Mr Heseltine's fears about
competitiveness. 'It is not the absolute level of executive pay that
shareholders object to. It is when you see shareholder wealth being
dissipated by management,' one said.
Others said there were better ways of curbing excessive pay, such as forcing
companies to make executive contracts easily available to shareholders. 'If
they were simply to go for proper disclosure, that would help a lot,' one
said.
The government could also set limits on favourable tax treatment for share
option schemes or pension arrangements which failed to meet guidelines
recommended by the UK's leading shareholder groups.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
<XX>
