FT  05 DEC 94 / International Company News: Ulster Bank paying IPounds 25m
for stockbroker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MACMANUS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ulster Bank, the Irish subsidiary of National Westminster Bank, has applied
for approval under Irish monopolies and mergers legislation to buy NCB, the
second largest Dublin stockbroker, for IPounds 25.5m (Pounds 25.1m).
The deal follows eight months of negotiation and will involve a payment of
IPounds 10.5m with another IPounds 15m over five years depending on
performance.
Mr Dermot Desmond, the broker's non-executive chairman and 56 per cent
shareholder, stands to receive more than IPounds 14m. At least IPounds 6m of
this will be paid initially, but Mr Desmond may actually receive a larger
portion up front as he is leaving the company. The rest will be split
between 35 other employees who own the balance.
